         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... Having decorated a vehicle designed for bulls ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... but the divine king Indra ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">but (in that way) why should I not ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">the Buddha lord, the teacher ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... having turned back, the Buddha lord ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... even (wor)shipping (with) shining lamp ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (falls?) full on earth. Thus indeed ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... I worship you (be)ing ... (with) the head [and] (the front head) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... this one inclined (towards) the Buddha ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... this one fearing the Saṃsāra ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... this sweet [and] charming voice (was heard) in the sky ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... compassionate. If ...</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="remarks">The leaf number 36 is repeated inside the string hole space on the verso side. Unlike in other cases in this mansucript, the number written inside the string hole does not deviate from the one written on the margin. This is true for the continuous series <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a32"/> until <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a36"/>.</note><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment">: the second strophe of the metrical passage in the tune <hi>viśikkonaṃ</hi> of the preceding fragment (<ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a35"/> b2).</note><note corresp="#a4" type="philcomment"><hi>ca</hi> could perhaps be the beginning of a proper name.</note><note corresp="#a6" type="philcomment">An oblique or other case form of <hi>cok</hi> 'lamp' has to be restored here.</note><note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment">Restoration to <hi>klawaträ</hi> 'falls' may be considered.</note><note corresp="#b5 #b6" type="philcomment">We are probably in verse here because of the unusal word order; the interpunctation also speaks for that.</note><note corresp="#b6" type="philcomment">Cf. the passage <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-yqii14"/>: a1. Probably the end of an adjective derived from an abstract, e.g. <hi>kāswoneyu</hi>.</note></p>
         </div>
